{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CcwN44McG2quxw73S1iMK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Before I write anything, a migration like this has a few forks that completely change the script — let me nail those down rather than guess, since moving `orders` (which almost certainly has a FK to `users`) in the wrong order will fail on load.\n\nKey questions:\n\n1. **Where is \"new database\"?**\n   - Same Postgres server, different database? (Can't do a cross-database query in Postgres — needs dump/restore, `postgres_fdw`, or `dblink`.)\n   - Different server entirely?\n\n2. **Downtime tolerance.** Is this a one-shot cutover where you can take writes offline, or does it need to be live/zero-downtime (which means logical replication, not a script)?\n\n3. **Data volume.** Thousands of rows or hundreds of millions? Decides `pg_dump` vs. batched `COPY` vs. logical replication.\n\n4. **Foreign keys & dependencies.** Does `orders.user_id` reference `users`? Any sequences, triggers, indexes, or other tables referencing these two? We need to move `users` before `orders` and re-sync sequences after.\n\n5. **Schema already exists in the target,** or does the script need to create the tables too?\n\nMy default recommendation, if this is a same-server or reachable-server one-shot cutover with moderate data:\n\n```\npg_dump --table=users --table=orders -Fc source_db > tables.dump\npg_restore --dbname=target_db tables.dump\n# then reset sequences: SELECT setval(...) for each serial/identity column\n```\n\nThat handles FK ordering and dependencies automatically, which a hand-rolled `INSERT` script tends to get wrong.\n\nWhich of the above matches your setup? Tell me the source/target connection shape and rough row counts and I'll write the actual script tailored to it."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5659,"cache_read_input_tokens"